<HEADLINE>
<P>
'TEACHERS TAKE EXTRA DUTIES' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This morning, on one of my so-called vacation days, I went to my school to fill 
out a stolen property report. My room had been broken into, again, and $1,100 
worth of my own personal property was taken in addition to $2,200 worth of 
school property. 
</P>
<P>
In the 15 years that I have taught at Kennedy High School my room has been 
broken into and/or vandalized five times, twice in the last two months. Last 
year, while I stayed after school to help some students, my car was stolen by a 
student. In past years I have suffered a fractured rib after having been 
knocked down by an automobile in the student parking lot, and in a separate 
incident I was bitten by a student. Although I am quite aware that there is a 
large segment of our society that receives a lower annual salary than that of a 
teacher, for some reason, at this particular moment, my present teacher's 
salary just doesn't look all that great. 
</P>
<P>
How many of your readers, other than policemen, can document job experiences 
such as my own? My college education has done little to prepare me for the 
realities of teaching (drug and alcohol abuse, pregnancy, broken homes, child 
abuse, parents who don't care) that I have to deal with on a regular basis. 
</P>
<P>
I would hope that all of this would not lead you to believe that all teachers 
have the same job experiences as myself. Most teachers are able to teach their 
whole careers without any outside problems, yet, I know for a fact that many 
teachers have had to endure hardships far greater than my own. 
</P>
<P>
CHUCK HALL 
</P>
<P>
Canoga Park 
</P>
</TEXT>
