Photo, COLOR,CRISPY CROP Ventura County produces about 25% of nation's celery, 
growing more than 33 tons per acre. Louis Gonzalez hauls boxes in which 
vegetable is packaged as workers harvest it in Camarillo field. Francisco 
Ambris chops excess leaves from newly picked stalk. Harvest is from November to 
July. DAVID BUTOW / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wild Art 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA011289-0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 4323 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 12, 1989, Thursday, San Diego County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Part 6; Page 1; Column 2; Entertainment Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1261 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
TEEN WRITERS' HEARTS SURFACE IN WINNING PLAYS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By NANCY CHURNIN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A teen-age boy seeks to spark a friendship into a romance. A man, frustrated 
with his job, reduces his wife to a prisoner. A hapless rich man in the 1930s 
enlists the help of a talented but poor young woman to conceive a musical. Five 
high school runners learn about themselves and one another on a cross-country 
track. A boy agonizes about the choice between applying to the college he wants 
to go to and his father's alma mater. 
</P>
<P>
Such are the subjects on the minds, hearts and pages of the winning entries in 
the fourth annual California Young Playwrights Competition. Three of the works 
are being presented (through Jan. 22) as full productions at the Gaslamp 
Quarter Theatre Co. The musical "Broads!" and the play "Not What the Doctor 
Ordered" -- the conflict about college applications -- are scheduled as staged 
readings Jan. 25-29. 
</P>
<P>
When the California Young Playwrights Project (CYPP) debuted in 1985 at the 
Gaslamp, even its founder considered it daring. Deborah Salzer, creator and 
project director, remembers being "terrified" after getting the go-ahead from 
co-founders at both the Gaslamp and San Diego city schools. 
</P>
<P>
"For the whole first year, I didn't even believe 
</P>
<P>
the program existed," she said. "I was afraid no one would write scripts and 
afraid no one would show up to see them." 
</P>
<P>
CYPP members began playwrighting workshops in local schools in March, 1984, 
collected plays in June and presented them in January, 1985. Audiences gave 
their approval, and the project, open to all California students under 19, has 
since expanded northward, teaching students in Orange County and Los Angeles as 
well. 
</P>
<P>
Salzer's involvement with teen-age artists dates from a decade ago when she was 
working in Harlem to start a theater company for young people. One challenge 
was finding plays with parts for teen-agers. Then she met Gerald Chapman, a 
veteran of a young playwright project in London, whom Stephen Sondheim had 
brought to the United States in 1980 to start the Young Playwrights Festival in 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
Chapman, now deceased, gave Salzer a handful of scripts the Young Playwrights 
Festival had produced for her student theater. In 1982, Salzer took the plays 
with her when she moved to San Diego with her husband, Beeb Salzer, who had 
accepted a teaching post at San Diego State University. 
</P>
<P>
It was on the basis of these scripts that Salzer convinced the San Diego city 
schools and Kit Goldman, managing producer of the Gaslamp Quarter Theatre, of 
the potential of a young playwrights program. 
</P>
<P>
In turn, the strength of the scripts at the Gaslamp has led to what Sarah Luft, 
a producer at KPBS-TV (Channel 15), said may become a young playwrights series 
on the local public broadcasting station. 
</P>
<P>
Last year, Luft accompanied her teen-age daughter to the CYPP festival because 
one of her daughter's friends was acting in one of the plays. She was so taken 
with the work that she decided to produce for KPBS the play about the troubled 
maturation of a young Mexican-American girl, "Simply Maria, or the American 
Dream." 
</P>
<P>
Josefina Lopez of Los Angeles, who wrote the semi-autobiographical "Simply 
Maria," is now in town making revisions for the TV production. Shooting begins 
in March for a summer airing. 
</P>
<P>
At 19, Lopez is now too old to compete in CYPP contests. However, her friend, 
Pamela Mshana, also of Los Angeles, is back for a second time. 
</P>
<P>
Last year, Mshana's "Ebony" told the story of a daughter of an unwed mother who 
tries to escape her mother's fate only to become an unwed mother in turn. Dell 
Books will publish it in a collection next year. 
</P>
<P>
This year, Mshana, an 18-year-old sophomore at New York University, addresses 
the issue of a husband abusing his wife in "A Toast to Leslie." 
</P>
<P>
Carla Kirkwood, an Emmy-winning director who was given her choice of CYPP plays 
to direct, said she selected Mshana's work because she was stirred by what 
Mshana was trying to say. 
</P>
<P>
"The situation that Pamela's play deals with conjures up the Joel Steinberg 
case," said Kirkwood, referring to the recent New York trial in which 
Steinberg, a lawyer, was tried for beating his illegally adopted daughter to 
death. 
</P>
<P>
For Lopez, Mshana and Holly Frenzel, the 16-year-old sophomore at El Capitan 
High School in Lakeside who authored "Broads!," the playwrighting contest was 
an introduction to CYPP. The three were among the 2,500 students who started 
their plays because of CYPP workshops in their schools. 
</P>
<P>
"Searching for the Big Dipper," a story about friendship by Beckie Andersen, 
17, a senior at Crawford High School in San Diego, was used in a workshop 
taught by local playwright Janet Schechter-Tiger. "Runner's High," by Michele 
L. Mitchell, 17, a graduate of Esperanza High in Anaheim who now attends 
Northwestern University, was also developed in a workshop, as was "Not What the 
Doctor Ordered," the story about a boy torn between applying to Stanford -- his 
father's choice -- or to the school he prefers. 
</P>
<P>
Lisa Kirazian, 18, a graduate of Patrick Henry High School in San Diego, who 
wrote "Not What the Doctor Ordered," did not know she would be attending 
Stanford University herself when she based the play on someone she knew in high 
school. 
</P>
<P>
Ironically, although CYPP's breadth and approval rating has never been greater, 
the prospective audiences have never been smaller. 
</P>
<P>
Salzer didn't realize that plays with modest casts would translate into modest 
advance ticket sales. Last year, the winning plays had large casts, and the 30 
actors brought friends and teachers to see their work. This year's full 
productions call for a total of 12 actors, some of whom come from SDSU. 
</P>
<P>
The important thing is that the students get a chance to see their work 
professionally mounted in an environment where their work is "respected, valued 
and safe," Salzer said. 
</P>
<P>
At CYPP, the young playwrights get their work seen by critics and read by 
theater professionals. This year, the selection committee included Robert 
Blacker, associate director and dramaturge of La Jolla Playhouse; Jessica 
Teich, literary manager, Mark Taper Forum; David Hay, associate director, Old 
Globe Theatre; Michael Harvey, professor of drama, San Diego State University; 
Margaret McKerrow, professor of drama, SDSU, and Will Simpson, artistic 
director, Gaslamp Quarter Theatre Company. 
</P>
<P>
Salzer said the rewards come opening night. 
</P>
<P>
"I always feel wonderful watching the playwrights watching their work," Salzer 
said. "When Josefina (Lopez) was working with us, she got accepted into a 
playwrighting program in New York. The night she had to leave for New York, her 
entire family came down to San Diego to see her play. She sat in a place where 
she could see the show and see her parents, who spoke no English, hoping that 
they would see the love and the humor in the work. Near the end of the play, 
the heroine decides to go off and accept a scholarship. She writes a letter of 
goodby to her family. She thanks them and tells them she will always be Mexican 
in her heart but is leaving to embrace her new country. 
</P>
<P>
"At that point Josefina started weeping because that was exactly what she was 
doing in real life. She was weeping because she was relieved to see that her 
family accepted her play and that she was sitting in a full house that liked 
her work. And I was sitting right next to her, handing her Kleenex and hugging 
her. 
</P>
<P>
"I was very happy and felt very alive to be a part of this young woman and her 
artistic development. A lot of what rewards me is the nurturing going on. I 
felt like her producer and her San Diego mother and her friend all rolled up 
into one." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Emmy-winning director Carla Kirkwood, left, is producing "A Toast to 
Leslie," a California Young Playwrights Competition winner authored by Pamela 
Mshana of Los Angeles. STAN HONDA 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
