<HEADLINE>
<P>
DIGEST: LONG BEACH; 
</P>
<P>
THEATER CHAINS INVITED TO SUBMIT PROPOSALS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Saying there are plenty of Long Beach residents who would flock to a downtown 
movie theater complex -- if one existed -- the local Redevelopment Agency is 
asking major theater operators to submit proposals for an 8- to 14-screen 
cinema complex. It would be constructed within a redevelopment area bounded by 
1st and 3rd streets, Pacific Avenue and Long Beach Boulevard on land that the 
agency would sell to the operator. 
</P>
<P>
Many of the city's old theaters have closed or been demolished over the years, 
leaving a dearth of movie theaters in most parts of Long Beach. The city's only 
two major complexes are both located in the southeast corner, on Pacific Coast 
Highway. 
</P>
<P>
Redevelopment officials say a number of major theater operators are convinced 
there is a strong local market to support a downtown complex as large as 14 
screens. The city has long envisioned theaters as an important piece of the 
downtown redevelopment picture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
