<P>
France has asked Syria to extradite wanted Nazi war criminal Alois Brunner, the 
French Foreign Ministry said. Nazi hunter Serge Klarsfeld, who tracked Brunner 
to Syria 16 years ago, described him as the most important Nazi war criminal 
still alive. Brunner has been accused of organizing the deportation of 100,000 
Jews from Germany, France and Slovakia to Nazi death camps during World War II. 
There have been reports that Brunner, 76, is responsible for reorganizing 
Syria's secret services. Syria says it has no knowledge of him. Brunner, 
sentenced to death in absentia by a French court in 1954, has been described as 
the right-hand man of Adolf Eichmann, the Nazi official who masterminded the 
extermination of Jews. 
