<P>
GARDEN GROVE; 
</P>
<P>
KOREANS HOPE TO RAISE $130,000 FOR SENIORS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Orange County Korean-American Assn. has begun a drive to raise $130,000 to 
establish a Korean senior citizen center. 
</P>
<P>
H. Andrew Kim, an association spokesman, said the organization recently 
received a $5,000 grant from Pacific Bell to pay such fund-raising expenses as 
postage and printing of information sent to Korean households in Orange and Los 
Angeles counties. 
</P>
<P>
The group, established in 1987, plans to locate the senior center in a building 
bought by the association, Kim said. 
</P>
<P>
The money is to help repay a $130,000 mortgage on the building at 9888 Garden 
Grove Blvd., which is now being shared by the association and Korean senior 
citizens, he said. 
</P>
<P>
"The association eventually wants to move out so we can put the elderly center 
in there, because the facility is too small to handle both groups," Kim said. 
</P>
