<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEW WEAPONS FEATURED AT FAREWELL; 
</P>
<P>
GRATEFUL ARMED FORCES SALUTE REAGAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ANDREWS AIR FORCE BASE, Md. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
President Reagan, flanked by new weapons of war, was honored today with a 
21-gun salute in an elaborate farewell ceremony by the military that benefited 
from his record $2.5-trillion defense buildup. 
</P>
<P>
A Marine band played martial music as Reagan, who will leave office Jan. 20, 
reviewed honor guards representing the Army, Air Force, Marines, Navy and Coast 
Guard in a huge hangar at Andrews Air Force Base on the outskirts of 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
Reagan, who presided over the nation's biggest peacetime military buildup, told 
the assembled 1,400 military men and civilians that being armed forces 
commander in chief "is the most sacred, most important task of the presidency." 
</P>
<P>
He dedicated a moment of silence for the 595 servicemen who died on duty during 
his presidency. "They are not with us today because they are at the right hand 
of God. . . . They are our heroes," he said. 
</P>
<P>
The President, sent off to retirement by the marching tunes of each service, 
looked on the verge of tears when the band played strains of Auld Lang Syne. He 
blinked and swallowed hard as he stood at attention for the goodby. 
</P>
<P>
In the background were some of the weapons that joined the U.S. arsenal during 
his eight years as President -- an Army Apache attack helicopter, a Coast Guard 
search and rescue helicopter, a Navy F-18 fighter, a Marine Harrier jump-jet 
and a B-1B bomber. 
</P>
<P>
The Defense Department declined to estimate the cost of the ceremony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
